    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
                <!-- transcription goes here -->
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName><name type="cognomen" key="Constantia"><choice><reg>Constantia</reg><orig>Costantia</orig></choice></name></persName>
                    <lb n="2"/>in pace. 
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>"Constantia (rests) in peace."</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <!-- notes go here -->
                <p> Line 1: <persName><name type="cognomen">Costantina</name></persName>: The
                    N has dropped before the S, a common feature of Latin inscriptions as evidenced
                    by the use of <hi rend="italic">cosul</hi> for <hi rend="italic">consul</hi>. I
                    have regularized the word in my encoding. This inscription has a double entry in EDB (20207 and 21659).
                    Both inscriptions have the same basic data, text, and decoration, aside from the
                    difference in how they spell the name. Both of these inscriptions are supposed
                    to be housed in the Johns Hopkins Museum, but there is only one in the catalogue</p>

                <p>The spacing is wide and irregular. The lines slant up and to the right and occupy
                    the upper half of the slab. The dove (7.7 x 20.6) is carved in the second line
                    on the right hand margin. The letters are roughly cut, and vary in size and
                    appearance. The smallest letter is the C is line 2 (3.6 cm), while the largest
                    is the P in line 2 (5.5 cm). Of the three As in the text, the first appears
                    without the third stroke, while the other two have a third stroke that runs
                    diagonally from the second stroke down to the baseline. The loop of the P does
                    not meet the <hi rend="italic">hasta</hi>. The first C has straight serifs at
                    the top and bottom, but the second C has a bottom serif that swoops upward, like
                    a G. The lower curl of the S is also smaller than the top; the O is fat and
                    round. There are no interpuncts on the stone and no words are broken by the
                    lines.</p>

                
            </div>

